            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Priya Herrera\u2019s name is a cartography of her family\u2019s journey. Born in Fremont to an Indian-American father who was an engineer in the burgeoning Silicon Valley and a Filipino-American mother who was a nurse, Priya grew up in a home that blended cultures and valued pragmatic solutions. From her childhood window, she watched the Bay Area's landscape transform, fascinated by the networks of freeways and the expanding BART lines that stitched disparate communities together. This early fascination with how people move set her on a direct path toward a career in public service.\n\nHer educational journey was a deliberate one, earning a bachelor\u2019s degree from UC Berkeley before pursuing her Master's in Urban and Regional Planning at UCLA. Armed with her degree, she was drawn to San Francisco, the city she saw as the ultimate urban puzzle. She joined the city\u2019s transportation agency as a junior planner, meticulously analyzing bus routes and pedestrian flow. A key turning point was her leadership on a controversial project to implement dedicated bus lanes on a major corridor. Facing down fierce public opposition, she used data and community outreach to demonstrate the project's benefits, solidifying her reputation as a capable and resilient leader. This success propelled her through the ranks to her current role as Director.\n\nNow, at 49, Priya\u2019s life is deeply intertwined with the city she serves. She lives in a minimalist apartment in Hayes Valley, a neighborhood chosen for its central location and vibrant street life. Her daily commute on the Muni is not a chore but a living laboratory for her work; she observes rider patterns and wait times with a critical eye. Amicably divorced for a decade, her most significant relationship is with her son, now a university student in Oregon. Their weekly video calls are a cherished ritual.\n\nPriya\u2019s aspirations are extensions of her career. She dreams of a San Francisco with a world-class, equitable transit system that reduces the city\u2019s reliance on cars. Her ultimate goal is to leave behind a legacy of connectivity, ensuring that a person\u2019s zip code doesn't determine their access to opportunity. She imagines a future where her son might return to a city that is more efficient, sustainable, and accessible because of the work she does today."
